<DOC><DOCNO> AP891020-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-89 1937EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-20 0372</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0382</SECOND><HEAD>Early Frost, Record Cold Hit South, Gulf Coast States</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Much of the South and the Gulf Coast shivered as the mercuryplunged Friday, snapping low-temperature records in 38 cities andtying them in seven others. The chilly weather was expected tocontinue into Saturday.   The low temperatures followed a storm that dumped more than 8inches of snow on north-central Indiana by Friday morning and 2 to6 inches over much of Illinois, Ohio, southern Michigan andsoutheast Wisconsin.   Snow fell in the mountains of northern Georgia and NorthCarolina during the morning. Snowfall was generally light, althoughthere was a two-inch accumulation at Beach Mountain, N.C., byFriday afternoon.   In the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT, 2 inches of snow fell inMarquette, Mich.; 5 inches in South Bend, Ind; 3 inches inMilwaukee and 1 inch in Fort Wayne, Ind., and Wausau, Wis.   Snow, often mixed with rain, fell from Wisconsin and Michigan tonorthern and west central Illinois. Rain, mixed with snow at higherelevations, extended from northern Tennessee to eastern Kentuckyand southwestern West Virginia. Rain and occasional thunderstormsreached from New York state to central New England and fell overthe northern coast of North Carolina.   Flood watches were posted for sections of New Jersey, RhodeIsland and Pennsylvania.   Winds gusted to around 35 mph in Knoxville, Tenn., and gustywinds raised blowing dust in the southern San Joaquin Valley inCalifornia.   Low-temperature records up to 72 years old were broken or tiedacross the South.   In Lake Charles, La., the temperature hit 32 degrees, snappingthe mark of 35 degrees set in 1939 and setting a record low for themonth. It was 32 degrees in Little Rock, Ark., the earliest freezeever recorded in that city.   A low of 22 degrees in Ozark, Ark., beat by 8 degrees the recordset back in 1917.   Records were also set in Pensacola, Fla. (35 degrees, 42 in1981), Mobile, Ala. (33 degrees, 39 in 1964) and Mena, Ark. (24, 30in 1925 and 1966).   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32degrees in Kalamazoo and Marquette, Mich., to 87 degrees in Yuma,Ariz.</TEXT></DOC>